Here are the public test cases for feature1_accessible_queries:
{
  "description": "Locate elements inside an HTML fragment using accessibility-oriented queries. Each request names the query strategy: visible text content, an associated form label, a placeholder, image alternative text, a title attribute, or a control's current display value. The query returns every matching element in document order; the report lists how many were found and, for each, its tag name and id. An optional CSS selector narrows the candidate set so only elements matching that selector are considered.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "locate",
        "by": "text",
        "match": "By text",
        "html": "<p id=\"by-text-p\">By text</p><p id=\"by-text-p-2\">By text</p>"
      },
      "expected_output": "count=2\nmatch=p#by-text-p\nmatch=p#by-text-p-2\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "locate",
        "by": "label",
        "match": "By label",
        "html": "<label for=\"by-label-input\">By label</label><input type=\"text\" id=\"by-label-input\" />"
      },
      "expected_output": "count=1\nmatch=input#by-label-input\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature2_text_content_query:
{
  "description": "Locate an element whose collected text content (the concatenation of all descendant text) matches a target, after a normalization step. By default the normalizer trims the ends and collapses runs of whitespace to single spaces, and matching is exact and case-sensitive. A mandatory selector restricts which elements are tested. Matching can be made substring-based instead of exact, and the two normalization steps (trimming, whitespace collapsing) can each be turned off so leading/trailing or repeated spaces become significant. The target may also be given as a regular expression tested against the normalized text. The report lists how many elements matched and each match's tag name and id.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "locate-content",
        "matcher": "some deeply NESTED TEXT",
        "selector": "#text-content-root",
        "html": "<div id=\"text-content-root\"><span> some </span><span><span id=\"text-content-span-1\"><span>deeply</span><span> </span><span> </span>NESTED</span><span id=\"text-content-span-2\"> TEXT </span></span></div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "count=1\nmatch=div#text-content-root\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "locate-content",
        "matcher": "deeply nested",
        "exact": false,
        "selector": "#text-content-root",
        "html": "<div id=\"text-content-root\"><span> some </span><span><span id=\"text-content-span-1\"><span>deeply</span><span> </span><span> </span>NESTED</span><span id=\"text-content-span-2\"> TEXT </span></span></div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "count=1\nmatch=div#text-content-root\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_visibility:
{
  "description": "Determine whether a referenced element is visible or hidden. An element counts as hidden when it (or any ancestor) is removed from rendering via a display:none style, a visibility:hidden style, a hidden attribute, or, for form controls, an input whose type is hidden; otherwise it is visible. The element is addressed by a CSS selector against the supplied HTML fragment. The report echoes the selector and the two complementary outcomes.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "visibility",
        "selector": "#visible",
        "html": "<div id=\"visible\">Visible</div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "selector=#visible\nvisible=true\nhidden=false\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "visibility",
        "selector": "#display-none",
        "html": "<div id=\"display-none\" style=\"display:none\">Hidden with display none</div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "selector=#display-none\nvisible=false\nhidden=true\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature4_class_assertion:
{
  "description": "Check whether an element carries an expected set of CSS classes. By default the check is order-sensitive: the element must carry exactly the requested classes in the requested order. A non-strict mode relaxes this so the element only has to contain all requested classes in any order. The element is addressed by a CSS selector against the supplied HTML fragment. The report states whether the check passed and echoes the element's actual class list.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "class",
        "selector": "#classes",
        "classes": [
          "class-a",
          "class-b"
        ],
        "html": "<div id=\"classes\" class=\"class-a class-b\">Classes</div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "pass=true\nactual=class-a class-b\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "class",
        "selector": "#classes",
        "classes": [
          "class-b",
          "class-a"
        ],
        "html": "<div id=\"classes\" class=\"class-a class-b\">Classes</div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "pass=false\nactual=class-a class-b\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature5_style_assertion:
{
  "description": "Check whether an element's inline styles include every expected CSS property/value pair. The check passes only when each requested property is present on the element and its value matches the expected value (whitespace is ignored in the comparison); a missing property or a differing value fails the check. The element is addressed by a CSS selector against the supplied HTML fragment. The report states whether the check passed and echoes the element's actual value for each requested property (empty when the property is not set).",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "style",
        "selector": "#styles",
        "styles": {
          "background-color": "indianred"
        },
        "html": "<div id=\"styles\" style=\"background-color: indianred; color: chocolate;\"></div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "pass=true\nbackground-color=indianred\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "style",
        "selector": "#styles",
        "styles": {
          "height": "100px"
        },
        "html": "<div id=\"styles\" style=\"background-color: indianred; color: chocolate;\"></div>"
      },
      "expected_output": "pass=false\nheight=\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature6_partial_object:
{
  "description": "Check whether one object is a partial of another: every property present in the expected object must exist on the actual object with a strictly equal value. The check passes when the expected object is a subset of the actual object (including when they are identical) and fails when any expected property is missing or has a different value. The report states whether the check passed and, for each expected property, whether it matched the actual object.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "partial",
        "actual": {
          "lorem": "first",
          "ipsum": "second"
        },
        "expected": {
          "lorem": "first"
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "pass=true\nlorem=match\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "op": "partial",
        "actual": {
          "lorem": "first",
          "ipsum": "second"
        },
        "expected": {
          "lorem": "second"
        }
      },
      "expected_output": "pass=false\nlorem=mismatch\n"
    }
  ]
}
